  \entry{windowFunctionsSpectralLeakage}{inbook}{}{}
    \name{author}{1}{}{%
      {{hash=LCS}{%
         family={Lessard},
         familyi={L\bibinitperiod},
         given={Charles\bibnamedelima S.},
         giveni={C\bibinitperiod\bibinitdelim S\bibinitperiod},
      }}%
    }
    \list{publisher}{1}{%
      {Springer International Publishing}%
    }
    \strng{namehash}{LCS1}
    \strng{fullhash}{LCS1}
    \field{labelnamesource}{author}
    \field{labeltitlesource}{title}
    \field{abstract}{%
    The purpose of window functions is to minimize a phenomenon called ``Spectral Leakage,'' which is the result of selecting a finite time interval and a nonorthogonal trigonometric basis function over the interval of analysis. Only frequencies that coincide with the basis function will project on a single basis vector, such as shown in Fig. 16.1. Signals, which include frequencies not on the basis set, will not be periodic in the observing interval (often referred to as the ``Observation or Observing Window''). The periodic extension of a signal with a period that is not equal to the fundamental period of the window (as in Fig. 16.2) will produce discontinuities at the boundaries of the observing interval. It is these discontinuities that cause the frequency leakage of the signal across the spectrum.%
    }
    \field{booktitle}{Signal Processing of Random Physiological Signals}
    \verb{doi}
    \verb 10.1007/978-3-031-01610-3_16
    \endverb
    \field{isbn}{978-3-031-01610-3}
    \field{pages}{175\bibrangedash 193}
    \field{title}{Window Functions and Spectral Leakage}
    \verb{url}
    \verb https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-031-01610-3_16
    \endverb
    \list{location}{1}{%
      {Cham}%
    }
    \field{year}{2006}
  \endentry

